We see that there is a certain period of negative time that these conditions
are satisfied, exactly as the solution~(\ref{exsol1}). The period of the
accelerated expansion can be adjusted by changing the constant $c$.
Just as the accelerating solution~(\ref{exsol1}), the universe is decelerating as
$t\to -\infty\; (\eta \to 0)$ and $t\to 0$ from $t<0 \;(\eta \to \infty)$
\cite{TW}. The singularity at $t=0$ of the function $S(t)$ is at an
infinite proper time future for any event with $t<0$, and our universe
simply separates into two with $t<0$ and $t>0$.

If the internal space is chosen to be flat ($\sigma=0$), the conditions
(\ref{cond1}) and (\ref{cond2}) give
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{cond13}
&& n_2(t) \equiv \frac{3}{4} \tanh(3ct) + \frac{\sqrt{21}}{4} > 0, \\
&& \frac{3}{2\sqrt{2}}\frac{1}{\cosh(3ct)}-n_2(t) > 0,
\label{cond23}
\end{eqnarray}
where we have chosen the plus sign in eq.~(\ref{ints}) since minus sign cannot
give expanding universe. We find that these conditions can also be satisfied
for negative $t$ as shown in Figs.~\ref{f3} and \ref{f4}, which are the
results again for $c=1$.
